      AFIN
      Geophysics and seismology
      Main activity / remark
      In the framework of the Antarctic Fast Ice Network (AFIN) physical properties, thickness and extend of sea ice and its snow cover are determined over the entire Atka Bay. These measurements are performed each year since 2010. The work was performed mainly and as a matter of routine by the wintering team of the Neumayer station. In the season 2020/2021, manual measurements of sea ice and platelet ice thickness, freeboard, and snow depth (drillings and stake measurements) were repeated along a 25-km-long transect at six measurement points across Atka Bay 8 times. Additionally, a ground-based GEM electromagnetic induction device and the GPS-equipped Magna Probe were used 4 times to measure total sea ice thickness and snow depth, respectively. To measure the water mass properties in the vertical water column, a Conductivity-Temperature-Depth (CTD) sensor suit was lowered through a drilled hole in October, November and December. For continuous measurements throughout the year, an ice mass balance buoy (IMB) and a snow buoy were deployed in late July. In the season 2021/2022, manual measurements of sea ice and platelet ice thickness, freeboard, and snow depth (drillings and stake measurements) were repeated along a 25-km-long transect at six measurement points across Atka Bay 4 times, 3 times for the first three sampling points only, and once at the first sampling point only. In addition, a ground-based GEM electromagnetic induction device was used 4 times to measure total sea ice thickness along the same transect. In order to measure the water mass properties in the vertical water column, a Conductivity-Temperature-Depth (CTD) sensor suit was lowered through a drilled hole three times between end of November and end of December. For continuous measurements throughout the year, an ice mass balance buoy (IMB) and a snow buoy were deployed in Atka Bay in beginning of July.

      Combined GNSS-Reflecto/Refractometry remote sensing for automated and continuous surface mass balance estimation on a polar ice sheet
      Geophysics and seismology
      Main activity / remark
      During the 2021/2022 Antarctic summer season, 3 GNSS antennas were installed in the vicinity of the German Neumayer station III. GNSS-RR data has been collected automatically and continuously since the installation and will be continued until the summer season 2022/23. The reception of GNSS signals is passive, non-destructive and therefore has no environmental impact. Available stake and AWS observations as well as density measurements obtained from the standard operations at NM III are used as ground truth for validating the GNSS RR results. The data is stored on site and regularly transferred via the NM III satellite infrastructure, allowing continuous quality monitoring after the summer season.

      Disciplines
      GrouZE
      Geophysics and seismology
      Main activity / remark
      After a long delay in Cape Town due to an extended quarantine of 40 days, the field work started at 27th of December 2021 at Neumayer Station III preparing the traverse to the southern end of the Ekstroem Ice Shelf. The traverse departed at 02nd of January 2022 and reached the joint camp with the ReMelt-Radar group on the 3rd of January. Within the next 10 days, we set up 15 three component broad band seismometer and 7 geodetic GNSS stations within 25km distance of the grounding line. All stations were revisited to gather a first data set and ensure correct technical functionality. The 2021/2022 work under the GrouZE project ended on 12th January 2022, when the camp at the grounding line was dismantled.

      Project Name/Number
      Disciplines
      Photovoltaic Testunit attached to Neumayer Station III - Building
      Technique
      Main activity / remark
      At the NMIII station, a pilot plant to determine possible energy yields and risks through the installation of photovoltaic systems have been installed. Various PV modules have been installed on the external facade of the station building. In order to test the actual suitability of the modules in view of the extreme weather conditions, pressure, suction sensors and strain gages have been installed on the modules. The yield of the PV modules oriented in different directions, during the polar day and the polar night and during the long time of the twilight in the transitional period was the main subject of the testing. The PV modules on one side of the building, the east side have been installed. Their data acquisition is in operation. Electrical energy produced by the PV modules on east side cannot be transmitted into stations grid, due to a broken electrical component. The low number of feeder flights due to the pandemic prevented the delivery of the spare part in time in the 2nd term of the season. The assembly of the modules on the north and west sides has not started due to this event. The evaluation of the data thus obtained allows conclusions to be drawn on the feasibility of a large-scale PV system at the Neumayer Station.

      Routine meteorological observations at Neumayer Station - snow height measurements
      Meteorology
      Main activity / remark
      As part of the snow mass budget monitoring at Neumayer-Station a continuously measuring, spatially averaging system was taken into operation on an existing mast in the station’s vicinity. The system receives and stores GNSS satellite signals (GPS, GLONAS, GALILEO) to deduce snow height and vertically integrated water vapour. After start of operations no further maintenance was necessary.

      Dr. H. Schmithüsen (AWI)
      Project Name/Number
      Disciplines
      SLIFT
      Glaciology
      Main activity / remark
      Neumayer Station is standing on snow. Because of accumulating snow. The station has to be lifted twice a year. In this process, each of the hydraulic supports is lifted and snow is filled underneath each of the 16 hydraulic support foundation plates. In order to investigates whether and how the snow used in this lifting process should be pre-treated to reduce settling, firn cores were taken underneath the foundation plates, in the vicinity of the foundation plates and in the surrounding of Neumayer station. The mechanical und physical properties of the snow (e.g. density, grain size) in the core samples will further be investigated in Bremerhaven, e.g. for high resolution density, grain size and micro-structural properties.

      Yearly maintenance airchemistry observatory
      Atmospheric sciences
      Main activity / remark
      Once again, due to Corona pandemic only a restricted summer season was practicable, but we succeeded in completing all necessary work to run the observatory for another year without cutback. Concerning technical issues, we installed a new uninterruptible power supply. This was necessary because the old one broke down during a serious blizzard event with so far never observed peak wind velocities >200 km/h on 13 August 2021. In December and January, the Air Chemistry observatory was jacked up. This procedure entailed an interruption of all measurements for several hours. Finally, the operation of the observatory was taken over by the new air chemistry over-winterer Hannes Keck, arriving at Neumayer on 17 January 2022. In spite of the short training period (just 4 weeks), Hannes Keck took on the responsibility for the Air Chemistry Observatory not thanks to the competent and dedicated instruction by Linda Ort.

      Yearly maintenance CTBTO 127DE Array
      Geophysics and seismology
      Main activity / remark
      IS27 is to be operated continuously with at least 98 % data availability over a year's time, which is required for an IMS station. Routine maintenance of the array is a prerequisite to ensure the high reliability and is normally carried out every year during the Austral summer between December and February. The condition of the equipment has to be checked, hardware and software upgrades have to be installed. Once again this year's maintenance work was canceled due to the corona pandemic. Nevertheless, the nine elements could be recovered from 2 m snow depth and were repositioned on the surface. Remote support was available all the time to keep data quality as high as possible.

      Project Name/Number
      Disciplines
      Yearly maintenance geophysics observatory
      Geophysics and seismology
      Main activity / remark
      During the winter of 2021, the twelve stations of the temporary network “EKS” east of Neumayer Station III were checked frequently. Between September and November 2021, the EKS network was brought back from the field for maintenance and preparation for the GrouZE project. In the Antarctic summer season 2021/2022, maintenance work was done at the permanent stations VNA2 and VNA3. The GrouZE network was deployed and the seismic station at Kohnen was visited and repaired by station personnel. The station DS4 at Forstefjell was visited in January 2022, and a problem with the data acquisition device was diagnosed. A repair in the field was not possible. The station NVL at Novolazarevskaya Station was visited in February 2022. WEI, SVEA, and UPST were not serviced this season. During the summer season 21/22, we started to integrate an automated machine learning model into the earthquake picking workflow. We implemented a model to automatically refine rough picks in order to reduce the picking workload. First tests were done and will be continued during winter 2022. The geomagnetic fieldwork consisted of taking manual theodolite measurements of the declination and inclination of the magnetic field on a weekly basis and gyro measurements for the determination of geographic North on a monthly basis.

      Main activity / remark
      In the field season 2021/22 instrumentation and operating procedures of the following atmospheric observations were handed over from one meteorologist to the next: • 3-hourly synoptic observations • daily upper-air soundings • weekly ozone soundings • continuous surface radiation and meteorological mast measurements • satellite picture reception (HRPT) • single column precipitation radar Logistik und Forschungsplattformen Operations and Research Platforms This handing over was not attended by a long-term member of the observatory as in other years due to the pandemic situation. A minimum of maintenance and service of all observatory facilities was carried out by the staff on site. Remote support from the long-term staff in Bremerhaven was provided as far as possible. Concerning automatic weather stations (AWS) the following was carried out: • AWS Søråsen: not serviced due do shortage of staff; it is expected that the station will remain above the surface for another year, even though measurements will be thoroughly affected • AWS Halfvarryggen: serviced as planned • AWS Kohnen: newly erected station in 2021/22; the work on site was carried out by members of the logistics and glaciology department Within DROMLAN, the meteorological observatory of the Neumayer-Station continued to support the weather forecasting services offered by the German Weather Service (DWD). This holds for all activities in Dronning Maud Land, especially all aircraft operations. This service is delivered in close cooperation between the Alfred Wegener Institute, Helmholtz Centre for Polar and Marine Research (AWI) and the DWD. Due to the pandemic situation, the forecasting service was provided from Cape Town, South Africa and Hamburg, Germany. Weather observations at Neumayer for the DROMLAN community were provided as usual.

      Remarks / Description
      PI: K. Jerosch (AWI) Air-born investigation of Sediment-rIch Glacial Meltwater plumes and sediment delivery from the shoreline of recently deglaciated coasts at Maxwell Bay, King Georg Island, Antarctica (SIGMA) Glacial meltwater rivers discharge large quantities of comminuted sediments, accessible for carbonate and silicate weathering reactions into fjords and channels of the Antarctic Peninsula. To understand the regional and global importance of glacier melt in terms of habitat change, we propose to spatially assess glacial meltwater discharge and to quantify affected areas in seawater transition zones and near glacier areas at King George Island. Goals 1. Georeferenced mapping of marine glacial outflow areas (plumes) of in front of eight glaciers 2. Comparison of normal freshwater conditions versus extreme discharge values time-delayed after extreme weather events by repeated stations 3. Survey erosional processes such as periglacial creeks at unglaciated coasts, which are directly linked to changes in the marine ecosystem (provision and delivery of sediment and solutes from the shore) 4. Implications for sediment and landscape stability by opportunistic vegetation succession in deglaciated areas. Study areas at King George Island (South Shetland Islands), West Antarctic Peninsula Starting in Potter Cove, a fjord well understood in spatial/temporal melt dynamics, we will expand the spatial analysis to coves in Maxwell and Admiralty Bay (seawater at the land-sea interface, glacial rivers and sediment surface plumes) considering areas with different lithology. We aim for mapping and measure marine glacial outflow areas (plumes) of in front of eight glaciers during the following missions (for the definition of one mission, please refer to chapter Data acquisition). • Maxwell Bay A. Potter Cove -> Fourcade Glacier (5-7 test missions, 10 missions) B. Marian Cove -> Moczydlowski Glacier (4 missions) C. Collins Harbour -> Polar Friendship Glacier (4 missions) • Bransfield Strait (D.) -> Polar Club Glacier (4 missions) • Admiralty Bay (mainly Ezcurra Inlet) E. Suszczewski Cove -> Ecology Glacier (4 missions) F. Anse Hervé -> Dera Icefall (4 missions) G. Goulden Cove -> Zalewski Glacier (4 missions) H. Lussich Cove -> Krak Glacier (4 missions) Methods According to Wójcik et al. (2019) with high-resolution photographs given by the Zenmuse X5s camera on an Inspire 2 quadcopter drone, we will be able to identify and quantify shapes and colours of glacial discharges as well as the recognition of plumes, due to its natural RGB colour model. Multispectral sensors of the DJI P4 Multispectral drone will be used for the analysis of water turbidity. Red wavelengths are applicable for identifying values representing low-turbidity and medium-turbidity waters (<70 FNU) and for identifying red and white sediments in water. High turbidity in water correlates with longer wavelengths such as Red Edge and Near Infrared. UAV technology will allow the observation of ice phenomena that prevent this type of analysis or interfere with its results. Devices to be used: • DJI P4 Multispectral drone: multispectral bands (5 cameras covering Blue, Green, Red, Red Edge, and Near Infrared bands) with global shutter, on a 3-axis stabilized gimbal with global shutter, on a 3-axis stabilized gimbal. An integrated spectral sunlight sensor on top of the drone captures solar irradiance, which maximizes accuracy and consistency of data collection through different times of day. When combined with post-processed data, this information helps to obtain the most accurate multispectral results. Autonomous missions and multiple intelligent flight modes are controlled by DJI GO 4 App. Dual battery, self-heating, battery redundancy, 98Wh. • DJI Inspires 2 drone with high resolution imagery data (Zenmuse X5s camera): integrated HD video transmission system, 360° rotating gimbal and a 4K camera, as well as the simplicity of Autonomous missions and multiple intelligent flight modes are controlled by DJI GO 4 App. Dual battery, self-heating, battery redundancy, 98Wh. 108kph max speed, 2kg thrust per rotor, maximum 27min flight time. Image Processing and storage: 5.2K@4.2Gbps RAW video recording, CineCore 2.0, integrated DJI CINESSD. Video Format: CinemaDNG and Apple ProRes 5.2K video support, H.265 and H.264 video codec support, while filming at 30 frames per second (FPS), and 16-megapixel images. The Zenmuse X5 camera with a standardized Red-Green-Blue colour model (sRGB) will be used to identify subglacial discharges and to validate the spectral images. • Positioning: a D-RTK 2 Mobile Station and NTRIP Compatibility will enhance the accuracy of RTK positioning without internet connection by connecting the P4 Multispectral to the D-RTK 2 High Precision GNSS Mobile Station and NTRIP (Network Transport of RTCM via Internet Protocol)2. Additionally, we will store the satellite observation data to be used for Post Processed Kinematics (PPK). • SBE 19plus V2 CTD: (Conductivity, Temperature and Depth with an auxiliary ECO NTU turbidity sensor for the multiparametric calibration of the drone-born multispectral bands and high resolution imagery data • GoPro5 camera: drop-down imagery of the seabed for benthic groundtruthing Data acquisition Both drones will be tested intensively at the Carlini Station helicopter-landing site before flying over open waters during varying weather conditions. The flight behavior will be protocolled in detail. One mission at a study area: the DJI multispectral drone flyover will be undertaken first, immediately followed by the Inspire 2 mission and, subsequently, the in situ turbidity measurements and seabed imagery from a zodiac. The drones will carry out precise, 2-km missions using the RTK positioning and the D-RTK 2 Mobile Station and an independent flight planning system controlled via the DJI GO4 App. The device are Wi-Fi-enabled, which allows the recording of the front camera transmission onto the controlling panel. An autonomous heating system allows functioning at low temperatures (down to -20°C). Forward-facing and downward-facing vision systems create an intelligent obstacle avoidance system that is especially useful in mountainous terrain. The drones are launched exclusively from land during SIGMA. We will reach the sites either via zodiak or by foot. We will avoid walking close to wildlife and onto vegetation. The flight missions are very short, about 40 min per drone and day, and very high (120 m). We can not 100% avoid possible short disturbances for birds during the takeoff and landing of the drones. Preflight, pre-takeoff, after-flight and battery update checklists will be applied. In case of an accidently broken drone, all pieces of waste will be taken and disposed accordingly. We will not perform any experiments or apply any markers. Flight specifications per UAV flight of 20-22 min will vary according to our Polish colleagues (Wójcik et al. 2019) due to topographic factors, including differing cove surfaces as well as uneven heights of the orographic obstacles: Area Covered: 0.20 -0.35 km2 No of Photographs: 450-1500 Flight altitude: 100-120 m Ground Sampling Distance (pixel resolution): 11-15 cm Total Mission Duration: 2 x 20-22 min each UAS (in total 80-88 min) Mean wind speed: < 10 m-1 Efforts to save the Antarctic environment or to reduce damage to an absolute minimum: The flight missions will be very short, about 20 min per drone, and very high (120 m). We can not 100% avoid possible short disturbances during the takeoff and landing of the drones. To keep the risk of disturbance as low as possible, we follow the established recommendations of the Antarctic Treaty System for the use of UAS near bird colonies (ATCM Resolution 2, 2004): - we will not fly over bird colonies closer than 600 m. - we will try to maintain a horizontal separation of 500m from the coast. - we will not make stationary flights or repeated passes over concentrations of wildlife. - we will avoid landings within a 1 km radius of any bird colony. If the video transmission signal is lost and the intelligent return function is turned on, the Inspire 2 and Phantom 4 will fly back to the starting point using the original route. In the DJI Go4 app, the battery charge level is permanently monitored. If it reaches a self-defined value of 20%, the drones automatically return to the starting point. The drones are launched exclusively from land during SIGMA. However, the app is also capable of defining the remote control as the return point, so that a safe return via return function is also possible from drifting vessels. Safety features of DJI drones: Sense and Avoid: Forward and downward vision systems enable the Inspire 2 to detect obstacles up to 30 m ahead, allowing for protected flight at up to 54 kph at a controllable attitude angle of 25°. Upward facing infrared sensors scan obstacles 5 m above, adding protection when flying in enclosed spaces. Obstacle sensing systems are active during normal flight, RTH and all Intelligent Flight Modes. These sensors are core components of the DJI FlightAutonomy system, which brings the intelligent features to the Inspire 2. Smart Return to Home (RTH): Forward and downward vision systems allow the DJI drones to create a real-time map of its flight route as it flies. If the video transmission system signal is lost and Smart Return Home is enabled, it is able to fly home along its original route, and change to a straight line when it regains a signal. As it returns, it will use the primary camera to identify obstacles as far as 200m in front, allowing it to plan a safe route home. It is also able to reconnect more quickly after losing Connection. Further, in the DJI Go4 App settings the user defines the battery level to initiate automatically a RTH. Intelligent Flight Modes: Obstacle avoidance is optimized when using Point of Interest and Waypoint modes, making complex shots simple and repeatable. Powerful Flight Performance: A new propulsion system optimized for power creates a new level of flight performance. The Inspire 2 flies at up to 108kph descends at 9 m/s and climbs at 6m/s. It can accelerate from 0 to 80 kph in just four seconds and flies at a max attitude angle of 40°. The two controller sticks are tuned for more sensitivity, making delicate maneuvers easier. More power also allows the Inspire 2 to fly in more extreme conditions, including over 2500-5000m above sea level (using optional dedicated propellers), and in temperatures as low as -20°C using self-heating Intelligent Flight Batteries. Increased Reliabillity: Reliability has been further enhanced through dual redundancy of key modules such as the IMU and barometer. The intelligent flight control system monitors the redundancy system, giving it accurate flight data. The new obstacle sensing system helps the Inspire 2 sense and avoid obstacles, minimizing the risk of collision. Dual batteries mean that if a problem occurs on one battery the other is able to continue flight long enough for a safe landing. At the same time, the Inspire 2 propulsion system is driven a PWM signal with serial port signal redundancy so that if PWM signals are lost, transmission will continue through the serial port. This propulsion system has been tested for thousands of hours to ensure reliability, when combined with key sensors and a dual-battery design, overall flight reliability is significantly enhanced.

      PI: I. van Opzeeland The current project arises from the need for drilling new holes following from the fact that the iceshelf tip on which the old PALAOA with the old boreholes (drilled through hotwater drilling in 2005 at 3 km from the edge) was located broke off in February 2022. We aim to use the holes created by the TRIPLE-IceCraft project (TWT Aachen and partners) during the 2022/23 season, as alternative opportunity to hotwater drilling for the PALAOA III hydrophone deployments. The TRIPLE-IceCraft features a diameter of 20cm, theoretically sufficient for our hydrophone deployment, and progresses by 5m/h downwards and up to 10m/h upwards. The latter implies a retrieval period of at least 10 hours for the 100m thick shelf, creating the risk of the bore hole to have narrowed by peripheral refreezing of the melted ice (i.e. freshwater), which we aim to prevent through deployment of sea salt in the borehole during drilling. The proposed project concerns drilling of four new holes (of which one trial hole) at 1, 2 and 3 km from the ice shelf edge, through the app. 100 m thick Eckström Ice Shelf. The boreholes will be used to deploy a new hydrophone in each hole to continue the PALAOA time series of underwater acoustic recordings. Only the hydrophone deployed through the northern most hole will be connected to a recorder module, which is regularly serviced by the overwintering team. The second and 3rd hole would serve as a future back up hydrophone set which can be connected to a recorder module upon requirement.

      Remarks / Description
      PI: A. Herber (AWI) Black carbon (BC) plays an important role in the radiation budget of the polar regions, both in the atmosphere, as well as in deposited form in snow. Upon BC deposition on a white (snow or ice) surface, its albedo decreases, less incoming radiation is reflected and more heat is absorbed warming the surface. This also can lead to earlier snow melt, reducing the surface albedo even further (ocean, land) to absorb even more radiation and thus warm up even more. As part of our project, we plan to collect snow samples for BC analyses from snow pits at regular intervals over four to eight weeks together with the measurement of the physical properties of the snow at Neumayer Station III. In combination with our planned snow pit measurements, continuous atmospheric BC measurements will be performed at the station's Air Chemistry Observatory using SP2-XR instrument starting in January 2022. With our measurements of BC in the snow deposited between January 2022 and summer 2023 we will try to connect the measured atmospheric BC deposition rates with the concentrations we measure in snow. With this we would like to investigate the BC interactions and feedbacks between the atmosphere and snow. The whole campaign serves as a pilot study for a planned combined aerosol experiment with AWI aircraft and ground investigations. Comparable campaigns on horizontal and vertical aerosol and BC distribution and their seasonal variability have never been carried out in Dronning Maud Land before.

      PI: M. Hoffmann, T. Grasse (BGR) According to the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty (CTBT), the I27DE infrasound station is operated at the German “Neumayer” Antarctic Research base as one of 60 elements of the infrasound network of the International Monitoring System (IMS). Infrasound stations measure micropressure fluctuations in the atmosphere. Therefore they are mainly focussed on the monitoring of the compliance of the CTBT with respect to atmospheric nuclear explosions. The approximately uniform global distribution of the 60 stations ensures the ability to detect any atmospheric nuclear explosion of 1 kiloton TNT equivalent or more by at least two stations. Besides I27DE, three other infrasound stations will be established along the coast of Antarctica. The Federal Institute for Geosciences and Natural Resources (BGR) operates the German National Data Center (NDC) for the CTBT and is responsible for the operation of I27DE, which will be carried out in close co-operation with the Alfred Wegener Institute for Polar and Marine Research (AWI). I27DE is an infrasound array with nine array stations. Each station is equipped with a microbarometer and a data acquisition system. Meteorological sensors are installed at the central station. A wind-noise reducing pipe array is connected to each microbarometer. The distribution of the inlet ports to the microbarometer in a wide area ensures the suppression of the influence of wind-generated disturbances. The central array control system is installed in the seismo-acoustic observatory to power the stations and retrieve the recorded data. The infrasound data are transmitted continuously in near real time with a maximum delay of 5 minutes to the International Data Center (IDC) in Vienna, Austria, sharing the permanent satellite link between the Neumayer base and AWI. I27DE is to be operated continuously with at least 98 % data availability over a year's time, which is required for an IMS station. Routine maintenance of the array is a prerequisite to ensure the high reliability and is normally carried out every year during the Austral summer between December and February. During this period, the nine array elements have to be recovered from the snow and re-installed on the surface. The condition of the equipment has to be checked and software upgrades have to be installed.

      PI: V. Schlindwein (AWI) a) Seismology The primary objective of the seismographic observations at Neumayer-III (NM) is to complement the worldwide network of seismographic monitoring stations in the southern hemisphere. Special interests focus on the detection of local and regional earthquakes within Antarctica. Long term monitoring of regional seismicity over many years may eventually allow a rather detailed mapping of seismic active regions within the Antarctic plate. This will contribute to a better understanding of current neotectonic processes in Antarctica. The local seismographic network at Neumayer-III Station comprises the Geophysics Observatory VNA1 near NM itself and 2 remote stations VNA2 and VNA3 on the ice rises Halvfar Ryggen and Søråsen, resp. Additionally to seismic broadband recording a small aperture detection array with 15 vertical seismometers placed on three concentric rings with a total diameter of almost 2 km is operated at station VNA2. This array is a powerful tool for monitoring local and regional seismicity. Other unattended seismographic broadband stations are operated at the Russion base Novolazarevskaya, at Kohnen Station, near Weigel Nunatak and at the Swedish summer base Svea. The seismic broadband station at Sanae IV is also included into the larger seismographic network. Additional recordings from seismic stations in and around Antarctica are retrieved via internet and are very helpful for reliable localizations of Antarctic earthquakes. As in previous years both remote stations VNA2 and VNA3 have to be serviced during austral season 2020/2021 by members of the wintering team and a summer staff. b) Geomagnetism The new Geomagnetic Observatory at Neumayer-III was built during January and February 2009 and the routine observations were carried on at the new site with just a rather short data gap. During summer season 2011/2012 a second 3-component fluxgate magnetometer was installed. It is a standard FGE fluxgate sensor which is the current worldwide observatory standard. This second sensor was placed on top of a deeply frozen in, stable pillar outside the measuring hut. The geomagnetic observatory comprises now a NS orientated STL 3-component sensor and a second FGE sensor oriented in magnetic North direction. A GSM-19 Overhauser proton-magnetometer is used for recording total intensity. All systems run at a sample rate of 1 second. For better absolute measurements of the field components also a second declinometer was installed on a stable pillar outside the measuring container housing. Continuous recording of the second system started in July 2013, however, still interrupted by some software problems. Since January 2014 we have been operating with no major interruptions anymore and in July we became am member of the Intermagnet organsiation. During summer season 2017/18 a high frequency magnetometer was installed. c) GPS recordings Contiunuous GPS recordings were carried on again and are now available. This is accomplished using a 2-band Ashtec Z-12 receiver with its antenna on the roof of Neumayer-III. Due to failure, the receiver was exchanged by Novatel. Converted data in Rinex format are available on request and might in future be downloaded from a web interface. These GPS recordings have been relaunched because they provide valuable informations for higher atmosphere reasearch.

      PI: D. Dietrich & E. Riehle (University of Konstanz) During our stay at Rothera station on Adelaide island we plan on investigating all three major hypotheses of our research project: 1) an increase in abundance and diversity of parasites (fungi, cyanophages) associated with the increase in temperature the past 30-40 years can be observed, 2) an increase of temperature (2-3°C) leads to increased parasite pressure (absolute abundance of cyanophages and fungi), loss of cyanomat diversity, increased susceptibility to foreign cyanobacteria species and increased toxin production (Mechanistic study in the field and laboratory) and 3) Cyanobacterial mats from the Arctic (Iceland or Svalbard), known to be frequented by migratory birds and in close proximity to nesting grounds, and Antarctic (specifically Rothera) show a similar species community composition of cyanobacteria and associated parasites. To address the hypotheses mentioned above we aim to collect different cyanomat samples around Adelaide island and on adjacent islands at sites known to be frequented by migratory birds. Further, we plan on conducting a field experiment where we use small incubation chambers to simulate an increase in temperature of 2-3°C, while monitoring temperature increase, toxin production, cyanomat community composition and parasitism. Together with samples that have been already collected by ourselves or our collaborators in the past 40 years, we aim to get a detailed understanding of the long-term effects of climate warming and its impact on cyanomat communities, toxin production and diversity and parasitism. On site, we will collect small cyanomat samples (max. 5 g each), which will be fixed in Ethanol and/or RNAlater and stored until shipping them back to the laboratory in Konstanz. Upon return to Germany, we will isolate DNA and extract toxins from all freshly collected samples, as well as the samples collected over the past 40 years. DNA will be subjected to Shotgun sequencing to get an insight into the present species, and toxins will be extracted and analyzed with LC-HRMS/MS.

      Remarks / Description
      Gondwana Station is used as a logistic base for field parties. The station is operated by the Federal Institute for Geosciences and Natural Resources (BGR). It is located on a small peninsula at Gerlache Inlet, Terra Nova Bay, Ross Sea. The station can be reached either by ship or airplane. The sea ice conditions are generally favourable for aircraft operation (including Hercules C-130) early in the season. Later in the season landings are only possible on Browning Pass west of Gondwana. In this case helicopter shuttle flights have to provide the linkage to the Gondwana Station. The Terra Nova Bay area is one of the few ideal locations for Antarctic stations in this part of the Ross Sea. Gravel terraces on a slightly sloped terrain provide sufficient space for station buildings and helicopter landing pads. The area is free of snow early in the season and relatively sheltered against catabatic winds which are generally channelled by the Priestley Glacier and deviated towards Hells Gate. The absence of Penguin colonies in the Terra Nova Bay area is another advantage of this location. The first station building was erected in 1983 during the GANOVEX III (German Antarctic North Victoria Land Expedition) as a bivouac hut. During GANOVEX V (1988/89) Gondwana was enlarged and upgraded from a bivouac hut to a summer station. During GANOVEX IX (2005/06) the station was restored. A new painting of the walls and a new waterproof roof membrane protect the station.

      Remarks / Description
      PI: T. Fromm (AWI) Antarctica’s ice shelves are the main drain for mass loss of the ice sheet and the interface to the ocean. A major control of this process are ice-ocean interaction. Tides are the most direct forces acting on the ice shelves, inducing vertical and horizontal motion and a recent study revealed a strong impact of tides on the ice flow rates at the Ekstroem Ice shelf (Fromm et al, in review). The northward flow of the ice stream is mainly modulated with 3 and 4 cpd (cycles per day), whereas the dominant vertical tides have a periodicity of 1 and 2 cpd and 10 times larger amplitudes than the 3 and 4cpd tides. Particularly the causes of the higher frequency tidal modulations are still poorly understood and observational constrains are sparse. During tide induced grounding line migration a thin water layer forms beneath the ice, friction becomes important for the tides and could cause the observed high harmonic tidal constituents. The thin water layer reduces basal drag between the ice and the bedrock and such enhances the ice flow. We propose to investigate these ice dynamic processes with a geophysical / geodetic study of an exemplary region of the grounding zone of the Ekstroem-Shelf ice. We intend to capture vertical and horizontal motions of the ice using GNSS stations along the ice flow direction, from the freely floating ice shelf to permanently grounded ice. A seismological network will allow us to locate icequake activity from sticky spots at the ice-bed interface, which act as pinning points within the ice. With the magnetotelluric method (MT) we can image the sub-ice ocean-land transition and the crustal structure beneath. Another objective is to estimate the volume of highly conductive sea water beneath the resistive grounded ice and to test for possible temporal variations related to tidal motion. The objectives of this project are in line with the already planned glaciological project ReMeltRadar which targets the same area around the grounding zone to estimate basal melt rates, ice rheology and local bed topography. Integrating the results of these two projects with previous research at Neumayer and the Ekstroem Ice shelf has the potential to establish the Ekstroem Ice shelf as a reference for small ice shelves in East Antarctica and to reveal key processes in ice-ocean interaction.

      The research and supply vessel RV POLARSTERN commissioned in 1982 is a high class ice breaking vessel and the major research tool for the German Antarctic program. The advanced scientific and technical equipment and ability to navigate in heavy ice conditions in almost all regions of the Arctic and Antarctic oceans provide ideal working conditions for almost all compartments of marine sciences, atmospheric as well as glaciological research (modernisation from 1998 till 2001). Since 1982 the ship regularly operates in arctic and antarctic waters with an average of 320 days on sea every year. The supply of NEUMAYER STATION III is a regular task. Lifting gears and scientific winches are designed for launching and recovery of devices and sensors, fishing and deep sea sediment probing. Hydro-acoustic survey systems such as Hydrosweep, Parasound and fishery sounders can be continuously operated. The fibre optic network connects bridge, winch control room, laboratories and all scientific working places with several servers and distributes information of the central data acquisition system. Altogether 24 scientific laboratories, aquarium and refrigerating rooms are placed at disposal. Additionally up to 15 mobile laboratory containers can be installed inside the ship on E-Deck (10) and at F-Deck (5). The weather station records meteorological data and provides forecast information and satellite imagery on sea ice distributions. Recently technical facilities and hydro-acoustic navigation aids have been installed to deploy ROV for deep sea missions.       Cruise leader: K. Gohl (AWI) Seismic surveying of glacial-marine sediments in the Bellingshausen Sea and Amundsen Sea sectors for studying the development of the West Antarctic Ice Sheet K.Gohl (AWI) The West Antarctic Ice Sheet (WAIS) and the Antarctic Peninsula Ice Sheet (APIS) are likely subject to highly dynamic activities during periods of climate warming as most of the WAIS base is grounded below present sea-level and most of the APIS is exposed to surface warming. Knowing their contribution to sea-level during times when climate conditions were similar as expected of a future warming Earth, requires reconstruction of their glacial advance and retreat cycles in relationship to bathymetric, topographic and oceanographic conditions. We plan to decipher the paleo-environmental processes of the southern Bellingshausen Sea and eastern Amundsen Sea as this region exhibits some of the most dramatic ice mass loss developments in modern times. We hypothesize that this sector has always been the most vulnerable location in Antarctica for early ice sheet retreat in most deglaciation periods. Data produced by using seismic reflection profiling will be used in conjunction with other geoscientific data to identify branches of the West Antarctic Rift System and study transport-deposition-erosion processes of glacially derived shelf sediments and the structural properties of sediments drifts on the continental rise. Up to 5600 km (ca. 3000 nm) of seismic profiles are planned to be acquired on the continental shelf and continental rise of the Bellingshausen Sea and eastern Amundsen Sea. This dataset will fill a major data gap in the Bellingshausen Sea sector and missing seismic connections in the Amundsen Sea, and will link to pre-existing seismic profiles as well as scientific drill sites. This will require up to 25 days of seismic profiling, incl. deployment and recovery of the seismic equipment and circumnavigation of massive sea ice. A 3000-m long digital seismic hydrophone streamer will be used to record seismic wave-fields generated by 4 airguns (GI-Guns Type 150 operating in True GI-Mode) at a shot interval of 10 seconds at 5 kn ship speed. In addition to the main seismic work program of this expedition, it is planned to collect 3-4 short seismic profiles (max 100 km = 54 nm in total) on the continental shelf of Ekström Ice Shelf region in the eastern Weddell Sea, if ice conditions allow. SO-Jelly PI: C. Gohl and J. Klages) Sedimentecholot PI: E. Weigelt (AWI) Subbottom profiling and mapping of the seafloor and shallow sediments with a main focus on glacigenic structures. CoreBell PI: J. Klages (AWI) The ice sheets of the West Antarctic (WAIS) and the Antarctic Peninsula (APIS) have been exposed to dramatic ice loss for decades. In case of WAIS this mass loss may kick start even faster retreat into subglacial hinterland basins, where ice is grounded as deep as ~2.5 km below sea level. Such WAIS collapse scenarios are simulated under certain environmental conditions that are forecast for centuries to come. To evaluate the recent rapid changes, geological archives provide valuable insight into both previous positions of the ice sheet and sea ice cover, as well as the mechanisms leading to retreat. High-resolution geological archives are also required for the southern APIS in order to reliably define previous retreat rates of ice sheets and sea ice. The aim is therefore to map the seabed in the so far little explored continental shelf regions of the Bellingshausen and eastern Amundsen Seas with multibeam, sidescan sonar, and sediment echosounders in high resolution in order to obtain more precise information about ice flow corridors of the last glacial and to understand subsequent retreat behaviour of the grounding line. Based on this information, we will target ideal locations for recovering sedimentary records that will allow us to define past ice-sheet bed conditions, establish the timing of past glacier fluctuations, constrain the mechanisms forcing past retreats, reconstruct past sea-ice cover, and identify variability of meltwater discharge and its role for past ice-sheet dynamics. In addition, we will try to sample deposits on the easternmost Amundsen Sea Embayment shelf covering the last interglacial period, which was characterized by temperatures that are expected for the coming decades and centuries. The knowledge of our work is urgently needed not only to understand the previous WAIS and APIS dynamics on different time scales, but also to improve models that attempt to more accurately predict the future behaviour of these ice sheets. Bathymetrie PI: B. Dorschel (AWI) Mapping of the sea floor with a main focus on glacigenic landforms. PI: Scheinert (TU Dresden) Temporal GNSS measurements on Peter I. Island PI: Kaul (University of Bremen) The goal of this investigation is the acquisition of in-situ temperature gradients for geothermal heat flow (GHF) estimates in the Bellingshausen Sea sector. The thermal state of polar continental crust plays a crucial role for understanding the stability and height of large ice sheets, the visco-elastic response of the solid-Earth due to unloading, when large ice caps melt and, in turn, the accuracy of future sea level rise prediction. The scientific community repeatedly outlined the importance of better constrained boundary conditions to enhance the accuracy ice sheet model performance for future sea level rise predictions. GHF estimates vary spatially on a regional level and have not been directly constrained by in-situ methods in this part of West Antarctica. PI: Spiegel (University of Bremen) The tectonic situation of West Antarctica has influenced its glacial cover, the West Antarctic Ice Sheet, both in the past and during the rapid ice loss of the last decades. Yet relatively little is known about the Cenozoic history of the West Antarctic Rift System (WARS), which dominates the tectonic evolution of West Antarctica since the Cretaceous. For this project, we will visit the Bellingshausen and Amundsen Seas, to collect samples for thermochronological dating and surface exposure dating. The new data will provide constraints on timing and kinematic relationships of the different branches of the WARS, on the tectonomorphic evolution of West Antarctica, which provides important boundary conditions for understanding onset and evolution of continental glaciation, and for controlling mechanisms and rates of deglaciation processes in West Antarctica in response to past climate change. Targets for the sampling campaign are the ice-free areas along the coast of the Bellingshausen and Amundsen Sea within helicopter range (i.e., ~100 nautical miles from the research vessel Polarstern), where we aim to collect bedrock samples and erratics. For obtaining information from the ice-covered areas, we will additionally collect marine clastic sediments close to the glacial outlets, using gravity or box corers. PI: Siebert (ITAW) The proposed project aims to collect data on the occurrence, distribution and response of cetaceans to seismic surveys during PS 134. The project uses visual and acoustic methods that are carried out during seismic investigations in the Amundsen and Bellingshausen Seas in close coordination between TiHo, JASCO and the geophysicists of the AWI. Noise exposure towards cetaceans and their vocalisations are recorded using an autonomous acoustic recording system (AMAR), which enables the identification, localisation and tracking of vocally active species within its coverage area. By means of visual observation methods (autonomous drone) we will collect data on distribution and behavioural responses during the seismic survey as well as habitat use of whales during the transits to and from the study area, respectively. The project is an interdisciplinary approach combining geophysical data with behavioural biology in order to assess effects of noise exposure on the behaviour of cetaceans. It will inform a future concept to manage and reduce the impact of seismic surveys on cetaceans in the Antarctic and substantially contribute to a sustainable strategy for exploring the Antarctic and conservation of its inhabiting marine mammals.

      PI: D. Steinhage (AWI) (a) ANTSI (approx. 79 flight hours) Antarctic sea ice plays an important role in the Antarctic climate and ecosystem. It is closely associated with ice-ocean interaction processes beneath ice shelves. We will conduct airborne electromagnetic (EM) thickness measurements of pack ice and fast ice in the eastern Weddell Sea to assess the condition of the ice and to quantify ice export from small coastal polynyas. We will also map the occurrence and thickness of the loose plate ice layer beneath the fast ice. This layer provides information on the occurrence of supercooled water that may form from beneath ice shelves during melting. The platelet ice layer therefore allows conclusions to be drawn about certain processes of ice shelf melting without having to examine the ice shelf itself. The thickness of the platelet ice layer can be determined with airborne EM measurements. The results will provide a new look at ice shelf melt processes in the eastern Weddell Sea and will provide important baseline data for future glaciological, oceanographic, and biological studies. Selected satellite orbit sections will be flown for validation of satellite remote sensing data. In addition, some (refrozen) melt ponds detected in remote sensing data will be investigated for blue ice on a test basis. (b) CAPS (approx. 6 h).       Aircraft additional information
      The ski-equipped aircraft POLAR 5 (Basler BT-67) is operated by AWI, was put into service in 2007 and is designed for scientific and logistic missions in Polar Regions. The BT-67 is an advanced DC-3 equipped with modern avionics, turbo prop engines and a combined ski-wheel gear. Loading capacity allows efficient logistic operations. The fuselage provides sufficient space for scientific installations. Large belly doors, several large openings in the cabin, wing stations for antennas and probes as well as powerful generators (15.4 kVA) are available for installation and running scientific systems on board. The operational range is more than 3000 km and the take-off ability with ski gear is up to 4,100 m sufficient for all elevations on the Antarctic inland ice plateau. In Antarctica POLAR 5 is integrated in the logisitcíc service in the frame of DROMLAN (Dronning Maud Land Air Network). The transport capacity of POLAR 5 is 14 passengers or up to 2000 kg cargo. POLAR 5 is mainly used for air-borne geophysical and glaciological survey missions as well as meteorological studies, in-situ air chemistry and radiation measurements. The aircraft can be adapted to different scientific programs. For further information see: http://www.awi.de/en/infrastructure/aircraft/research_aircraft/ Polar 5
